{"authors":"Kelly Redmond::Desert Research Institute Reno--", "title":"A Perspective on the PACE Post-doctoral Fellow Program", "abstract":"During the 30th Annual Climate Diagnostics and Prediction Workshop at State College PA in 2005, Lisa Goddard originated an idea that after further development became the Post-docs Applying Climate Expertise (PACE) Program. The developmental process was considerably enhanced by participation on US CLIVAR committees; CLIVAR embraces a wide spectrum from basic understanding of how climate operates to the application of that understanding for human and environmental benefit. The basic structure and application process for PACE are described in other talks in this session. The program is currently supported by NOAA but the model is potentially applicable to a wide range of agencies. A key concept is the stipulation of deliberate co-production of knowledge and cross-culture fertilization, making this program especially attractive for agencies and groups operating in a public arena. The approach taken is more difficult to implement because of the two-stage process. The oversight committee, which includes recent participants, continues to tinker with ways to streamline and improve the rather unusual and more lengthy application process, which is considerably more complex than most post-doc applications. One issue that remains to be better resolved is what is meant by the term “climate expert,” a phrase that means different things to different people in the climate community itself, including the level of breadth and depth of a complicated subject like climate. The “graduates” of this program have considered PACE to be a positive and very worthwhile experience in terms of broadening their professional portfolio and conceptualization of the use of information from climate science and allied disciplines. The counterpart decision-making institutions have likewise been very supportive of the program and its outcomes.", "url":"https://agu.confex.com/agu/fm15/meetingapp.cgi/Paper/85197", "section":""} 
