{"authors":"Alyson Santoro::University of Maryland Center for Environmental Science--", "title":"Dynamic nitrous oxide cycling in Chesapeake Bay", "abstract":"Nitrous oxide (N2O) emissions to the atmosphere from coastal areas, the timescales over which they vary, and the organisms controlling these fluxes are poorly understood. To better characterize N2O dynamics in the Chesapeake Bay, we measured ammonia oxidation and N2O production rates in August and September 2013 in the mesohaline region of the Chesapeake Bay during low oxygen conditions. Surface N2O saturation values ranged from 95 to 231%, with the northernmost transect being a sink for atmospheric N2O. Ammonium oxidation rates were greatest at the interface between ammonium-rich bottom water and oxygenated surface water, ranging between 15 and 133 nM h-1. N2O profiles suggest a source of N2O at the pycnocline and N2O consumption below the pycnocline. An engineering ‘control volume’ budget was used to estimate N2O production and consumption along a 21 km region in the Chesapeake Bay. Advective and diffusive processes were separated from internal N2O production and consumption processes, yielding estimates of atmospheric N2O flux between -0.05 to 0.06 nM h-1; these values agree with estimates of N2O production from nitrification rate measurements and reasonably explain N2O concentration profiles. Despite the high rates of ammonia oxidation measured during the study period, abundance of ammonia-oxidizing bacteria and archaea as determined by quantification of the amoA gene was very low. Our study shows that N2O emissions from the Chesapeake Bay are variable over multiple time and spatial scales and that the Bay can act as both a source and a sink for N2O during stratified summer conditions.", "url":"https://agu.confex.com/agu/fm15/meetingapp.cgi/Paper/85619", "section":""} 
