{"authors":"Nicole Khan::Rutgers University--Erica Ashe::Rutgers University New Brunswick--Ben Horton::Rutgers University New Brunswick--Gilles Brocard::University of Pennsylvania--Andrea Dutton::University of Florida--Simon Engelhart::University of Rhode Island--Robert Kopp::Rutgers University New Brunswick--David Hill::Oregon State University--W Peltier::University of Toronto--Frederick Scatena::University of Pennsylvania--", "title":"PP43C-2295: Timing and magnitude of the Caribbean mid-Holocene highstand", "abstract":"We present a database of published and new relative sea-level (RSL) data for the past 13 ka, which constrains the Holocene sea-level histories of the Caribbean coast of Central and South America (Florida Keys, USA to Guyana) and the Bahamas and Greater and Lesser Antilles islands. Our evaluation of mangrove peat and Acropora palmata sea-level indicators from geological investigations provides 503 sea-level index points and 242 limiting dates. We subdivide the database into 21 regions based on the availability of data, tectonic setting, and distance from the former Laurentide ice sheet. Most index points (75%) and limiting dates (90%) are <8 ka, although there is an unusual temporal distribution with the greatest amount of the data (~28%) occurring between 6-8 ka. We reassess and screen radiocarbon and U/Th ages of mangrove peat and coral data. We use the stratigraphic position (overburden thickness) of index points account for sediment compaction, and use the paleotidal model of Hill et al. (2011) to account for Holocene changes in paleotidal range. A noisy-input Gaussian process regression model calculates that the rates of RSL change were highest during the early Holocene (3-8 mm/yr) and have decreased over time (< 2 mm/yr), which is related to the reduction of ice equivalent meltwater input and collapse of the proglacial forebulge during the Holocene. The sea-level reconstructions demonstrate that RSL did not exceed the present height (0 m) during the Holocene in the majority of locations, with the exception of a small highstand (<2 m) on the northern coast of South America along the Orinoco Delta and Suriname/Guyana located furthest away from the former Laurentide Ice Sheet. The different sea-level histories are an ongoing isostatic response to deglaciation of the Laurentide Ice Sheet and suggest subsidence resulting from collapse of the proglacial forebulge reaches further south than previously considered.", "url":"https://agu.confex.com/agu/fm15/meetingapp.cgi/Paper/85947", "section":"Paleoceanography and Paleoclimatology"} 
