{"authors":"Yuan Tian::ITAG Institute of Theoretical and Applied Geophysics, Peking University--", "title":"3-D shear wave velocity structure beneath Northeastern China: An active craton margin", "abstract":"Northeast China (NEC, hereinafter) is a relatively complex block in Northeast Asia, which was formed in Paleozoic and Mesozoic eras due to the closing of Paleoasian Ocean (west) and the subduction of ancient Pacific plate (east). Unlike its neighbor North China Craton(NCC), NEC is not a typical craton but more like a craton margin which is more active and could probably tell us more about how a craton-like block is affected by subduction. It is a best place to study intra-continental volcanism: Mesozoic and Cenozoic volcanoes are widespread in the whole area, resulting in many famous volcanic zones: Changbai and Jingpohu in the east, Wudalianchi in the north, Arshan and Dalenuor in the west. Here we try to find the seismic evidence of where these volcanoes originated from and how they indicate the possible inner connection between the subduction of slabs and the evolution of NEC. We use dispersion curves respectively obtained from earthquake Two-Station Method (TSM)and Ambient Noise Tomography (ANT) to invert 3-D shear wave velocity structure beneath NEC. Unlike Helmhotz and Ekional tomography who requires evenly distributed station but can give estimates of uncertainty automatically, the TSM method could be done with uneven stations and more important, could obtain phase velocities of long periods and with less noise. We first get high - resolution tomographic figure of a wide range from 6s to 160s and give estimate of uncertainties of each period by bootstrap method. After obtaining high-resolution phase velocity maps, we invert for shear wave velocity using the Bayesian Monte-Carlo method of Shen et al., 2013, in which the Moho depth is constrained by receiver function results from Tao et al., 2014. Our results shows that the sources of the volcanoes are not the same: Changbai has the strongest and deepest source which may be directly supplied by a mid-lower mantle source; Arshan and Dalenuor have strong low velocity anomaly in upper mantle but vanish when going deeper; Wudalianchi has a shallowest source which only confines in crust and uppermost mantle and may come from low velocity zones in the east through preexisting faults.", "url":"https://agu.confex.com/agu/fm15/meetingapp.cgi/Paper/86019", "section":""} 
