{"authors":"Jefferson Chang::Oklahoma Geological Survey University of Oklahoma--Kevin Crain::Oklahoma Geological Survey--", "title":"NS42A-02: Semi-Infinite Geology Modeling Algorithm (SIGMA): a Modular Approach to 3D Gravity", "abstract":"Conventional 3D gravity computations can take up to days, weeks, and even months, depending on the size and resolution of the data being modeled. Additional modeling runs, due to technical malfunctions or additional data modifications, only compound computation times even further. We propose a new modeling algorithm that utilizes vertical line elements to approximate mass, and non-gridded (point) gravity observations. This algorithm is (1) magnitudes faster than conventional methods, (2) accurate to less than 0.1% error, and (3) modular. The modularity of this methodology means that researchers can modify their geology/terrain or gravity data, and only the modified component needs to be re-run. Additionally, land-, sea-, and air-based platforms can be modeled at their observation point, without having to filter data into a synthesized grid.", "url":"https://agu.confex.com/agu/fm15/meetingapp.cgi/Paper/86140", "section":"Near Surface Geophysics"} 
