{"authors":"Xi Peng::China University of Geosciences Wuhan--", "title":"The abstract title MUST be entered in initial upper case, for example: Mark th", "abstract":"The new seismic reflection dataset in south Java provide detailed structures of the southern Java forearc system. The plate interface is expressed as irregular surface in the western part and a continuous smooth surface in the eastern area. This observation coincides with the higher uplift of the western part of the forearc high. Cluster of shallow earthquakes can be observed near the western part of Java trench. Deformation of the forearc high is more intense in the west as compared to that in the east, consistent with higher uplift of the western part of the forearc high. However, the landward portion of compressional structures still can be observed within the whole forearc basin sediments. Backthrusting of the accretionary wedge can be observed, similar to that in the Mentawai forearc basin. The higher uplift of the forearc high has separated the Pliocene sediments deposited in the forearc basin and in the forearc high. Therefore, we suggest that this uplift is after the Pliocene. A morphological break of the top of the accretionary wedge can be recognized to the south of the forearc high, marking the boundary between the forearc high thrust with those in the frontal wedge. We suggest that the compressional structures developed in the southern Java forearc have similar features with those in the southern Sumatra forearc. However, some part of the forearc high has been abruptly deformed possibly due to the subduction of higher relief in the oceanic plate, similar to the Roo Rise. The new seismic reflection dataset in south Java provide detailed structures of the southern Java forearc system. The plate interface is expressed as irregular surface in the western part and a continuous smooth surface in the eastern area. This observation coincides with the higher uplift of the western part of the forearc h