{"authors":"Ata Elias::American University of Beirut--", "title":"The Qartaba Backthrust: An Active Fault In Central Mt-Lebanon.", "abstract":"Compression along the N25E, Lebanese Restraining Bend of the ~N-S striking Dead Sea Transform is accommodated by folding and thrusting within the Mt-Lebanon range (~3100m asl). Mt-Lebanon Thrust system lying west of Mt-Lebanon is an east-dipping crustal ramp best represented onshore by a west-dipping monocline known as the Lebanese Flexure. Other active structures accommodating compression are west-vergent folds and east-dipping thrusts, mostly outside central Mt-Lebanon. The Qartaba Fault, ~14km long, striking NE-SE in central Mt-Lebanon is thus an exception that we first document. It runs along the base of the eastern flank of Jej-Mountain: a wide box-shaped anticline. The Lebanese Flexure forms the western flank of Jej-Mountain. In many places of the eastern flank along the Qartaba Fault, the Mid-Jurassic layers of the mountain form a steep, NE-SW trending, 200m high, cliff overthrusting nearly vertical, east-dipping layers of the Upper-Jurassic to Lower Cretaceous units. The faulted contact in-between dips 30-35 degrees westward in opposite vergence to the Flexure and the overall folded structures of Mt-Lebanon range. We interpret this Qartaba Fault as a west-dipping backthrust ramp connected at depth with the east-dipping, blind ramp of the Lebanese Flexure. In places towards the base of the steep cliff an irregular, smooth, lighter-colored surface is located at the tip of the fault trace between the Jurassic rocks of the hanging wall and the slope material accumulated at its base. The presence of polished patches and its position strongly suggest a co-seismic origin of the scarp with a relatively recent rupture free face. In a trench we opened over the fault trace at base of the scarp, we uncovered alluvial material on the eastern side clearly folded and faulted in a thrust wedge position underlying the blocks of Jurassic rocks to the west. Preliminary Radiocarbon ages show that the sediments and deformation are Holocene in age. Additional dating results are expected. The Jej-Mountain is an east-vergent anticline growing over the west-dipping Qartaba backthrust in central Mt-Lebanon, contributing to the accommodation of shortening and compression along the restraining bend. This is in contradiction with all previous studies of the area.", "url":"https://agu.confex.com/agu/fm15/meetingapp.cgi/Paper/86766", "section":""} 
